net.hudup.core.data

Class DataConfig

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.hudup.core.data.PropList
      • net.hudup.core.data.DataConfig
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, TextParsable
    Direct Known Subclasses:
    SysConfig

    public class DataConfig
extends PropList
    Configuration utility class stores configuration properties. Each property is a pair of key and value. A popular key is unit which represents a CSV file, database table, Excel sheet, etc. Unit is used to store object such as user profile, item profile, rating matrix, etc. This class is very necessary to configure many objects. Moreover it contains many constants and static utility methods for processing data. This class inherits directly from the class PropList. As a convention, an DataConfig object is called configuration.
    Version:
    10.0
    Author:
    Loc Nguyen

    Serialized Form

      • getContextTemplateProfileUnit

        public java.lang.String getContextTemplateProfileUnit(int ctxTemplateId)
        Each template owns a table so-called template profile table, each row of table corresponds to a value assigned to template and such value is id of row. Such profile table is called unit. For example, the name of this table has format: hdp_context_template_1_profile where "1" is template id. This method gets the name of unit of template profile having specified identifier.
        Parameters:
        ctxTemplateId - specified identifier of template.
        Returns:
        name of unit of template profile having specified identifier.

      • fillUnitList

        public void fillUnitList(UnitList unitList)
        Filling in the internal unit list by specified unit list unitList. Concretely, if unit "item" does not exist in the internal unit list but it exists in the specified parameter unitList then "item" is put into the internal unit list.
        Parameters:
        unitList - The specified unit list

      • putUnitList

        public void putUnitList(UnitList unitList)
        Force to fill in the internal unit list by specified unit list unitList. Concretely, if unit "item" exists in the specified parameter unitList, it is put into the internal unit list instead of whether or not it exists in the internal unit list.
        Parameters:
        unitList - The specified unit list
